    {
      "id": "b5433f390b73c718e9a1fa6eb4040aa4e2de0d61",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-05 03:04:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)\n\nAnd yes, we do support large pages. Always were.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8a55d0e05f5246ab8f95262d60ac11da85e81cc0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-06 14:03:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nOleg, I see we need to support large pages, but current 2.x seems lack of this.\n\nIn mdt_readpage(), start and end hash is stored in each directory page, if client page is bigger than server page, the hash value read by client should not be able to cover the range the client page really holds. eg, if client page is 8k, twice the size of server page, and this dir happens has 8k bytes of data, so on server side, it's two pages, and each page stores the start and end hash, but client treat them as one page, and will assume the hash range of the first server page as its, finally this should lead to problem.\n\nTo fix it, server should know the page size of client, and package directory entries into reply buffers according to client page size.\n\nPlease correct me if I misunderstood.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ae8ef34883bf41941e38bf1d591c957af2f691eb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-06-06 19:29:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIn the 1.x code for a readdir with a client request > server PAGE_SIZE the MDS would fill in the rest of the request (beyond i_size) with fake directory entries, one for each block needed to fill the rest of the request.\n\n        bh = NULL;\n        if (*off < i_size_read(inode)) {\n                int err = 0;\n                  \n                bh = ext3_bread(NULL, inode, *off>>blkbits,\n                                0, &err);\n                :\n                :\n        }\n        if (!bh) {\n                struct ext3_dir_entry_2 *fake = (void *)buf;\n                memset(fake, 0, sizeof(*fake));\n                fake->rec_len = cpu_to_le16(blksize);\n        }\n\nThis is fine for a few pages, but is very inefficient if the RPC size is 1MB and the directory size is only 4kB (which is very typical), since there will always be 1MB of data sent over the wire.\n\nI would hope that for 2.x we can handle this at the client, either by filling in the lu_dirpage structures correctly to address the full hash range that fits into the client-side PAGE_SIZE, or by having the clients/servers agree to pack MDS_READPAGE requests in multiples of 4kB over the wire, with one lu_dirpage stored every 4kB in the client page cache, and the client needs to check (and pad, if necessary) the larger pages.\n\nIt may be that for compatibility reasons we need to assume servers are always filling in readdir requests with an lu_page every 4kB, and clients will need to handle this locally by doing lookups within a page (for PAGE_SIZE > 4kB) for hash values higher than the hash range in the first lu_dirpage.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "eb882a3c87f5fdfc04359a391818d62f01b61a82",
